\begin{figure}
\centering
\includegraphics[clip,width=0.48\textwidth]{fig5.pdf}

\caption{(Color online) Temperature dependence of the mean-value of the
continuum part of the sub-gap spectrum, $\omega_c(T)$, for a range of
hybridization strengths $\Gamma$.}

\label{fig4a}
\end{figure}

We first consider how the temperature dependencies of the key spectral
characteristics change for different values of $\Gamma$. The
$\delta$-peak position $\omega_\delta=\epsilon$ does not vary with
temperature. The continuum mean, $\omega_c$, shown in
Fig.~\ref{fig4a}, starts from $\omega_c(T=0) \approx \epsilon$ for
$\Gamma < \Gamma_c$, while for $\Gamma \gtrsim \Gamma_c$ it starts
from values close to the gap edge (this peculiar low-temperature
behavior will be explained in subsection~\ref{w}). In the temperature
range $T \lesssim \Delta$, $\omega_c$ is a decreasing function of $T$
for all cases where $\epsilon$ is close to the gap edge (i.e., in deep
doublet and in deep singlet phases), while it is non-monotonic or
increasing for $\epsilon \ll \Delta$ (i.e., in the transition range
with Shiba states deep in the gap), see Fig.~\ref{fig4a}. 

